{"parse":{"title":"Loop (education)","pageid":3865547,"revid":798830082,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Looping</b>, in <a href=\"/wiki/Education\" title=\"Education\">education</a>, refers to the practice of a <a href=\"/wiki/Teacher\" title=\"Teacher\">teacher</a> remaining with the same group of <a href=\"/wiki/Students\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Students\">students</a> for more than one <a href=\"/wiki/School_year\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"School year\">school year</a>. For example, a teacher who teaches a <a href=\"/wiki/Third_grade\" title=\"Third grade\">third grade</a> class and then goes on to teach the same students, the following year, for the <a href=\"/wiki/Fourth_grade\" title=\"Fourth grade\">fourth grade</a>.\n</p><p>This is distinct from the teacher of a multi-age class, who teaches a specific range of <a href=\"/wiki/School_grades_(US)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"School grades (US)\">school grades</a> together. In this case, although each child remains with the same teacher for multiple years, the group of students being taught changes annually as older children leave the group and are replaced by younger students entering.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Looping is usual in <a href=\"/wiki/Waldorf_education\" title=\"Waldorf education\">Waldorf education</a>, where the traditional goal has been for a primary teacher to remain as the lead teacher of a class for eight consecutive years, though in conjunction with numerous specialized teachers;<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> in recent decades, many schools have been reducing the loop to a shorter interval.<sup class=\"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">&#91;<i><a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed\" title=\"Wikipedia:Citation needed\"><span title=\"Which schools? How many? According to what data? (May 2016)\">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Benefits\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Benefits</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Disadvantages\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Disadvantages</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Benefits\">Benefits</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Loop_(education)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Benefits\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Educational advantages to having a single teacher have been found, including:\n</p>\n<ul><li>Teachers gain extra teaching time.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li>Teachers increase their knowledge about a child\u2019s intellectual strengths and weaknesses increases in a way that is impossible to achieve in a single year,<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li>Improved standardized test scores.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li>Long term teacher-student relationships have been noted to result in an emotional and intellectual climate that encourages thinking, risk-taking, and involvement.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Disadvantages\">Disadvantages</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Loop_(education)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Disadvantages\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Potential disadvantages of looping include:\n</p>\n<ul><li>Restricting the ability of teacher to perfect a lesson through repetition<sup id=\"cite_ref-Atlantic_8-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Atlantic-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li>Conflict/tension between students and teachers is not always resolved<sup id=\"cite_ref-Atlantic_8-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Atlantic-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li>Lapses in an instructor's teachings aren't necessarily corrected later on by a different instructor<sup id=\"cite_ref-Atlantic_8-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Atlantic-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li>A single teacher defines the character of the individual class, meaning each class carries with it its own unique and observable strengths and weaknesses throughout the looping grades.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Atlantic_8-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Atlantic-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Loop_(education)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Mulcahy, Dennis. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.mun.ca/educ/faculty/mwatch/win2000/mulcahy.html\">\"Multiage And Multi-Grade: Similarities And Differences\"</a><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">8 November</span> 2010</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Multiage+And+Multi-Grade%3A+Similarities+And+Differences&amp;rft.aulast=Mulcahy&amp;rft.aufirst=Dennis&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.mun.ca%2Feduc%2Ffaculty%2Fmwatch%2Fwin2000%2Fmulcahy.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ALoop+%28education%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Heiner Ullrich, <a href=\"/wiki/Rudolf_Steiner\" title=\"Rudolf Steiner\">Rudolf Steiner</a>, <i>Prospects: the quarterly review of comparative education</i>, v. XXIV, no. 3/4, pp. 555-572. UNESCO 1994.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Ratzki, A. (1988, Spring). \"The remarkable impact of creating a school community: One model of how it can be done.\" <i>American Educator</i>, 12, 10-43.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Jacoby, D. (1994, March). \"Twice the learning and twice the love\" <i>Teaching K-8</i>,24(6), 58-59</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-5\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">George, P.S. (1987). <i>Long term teacher-student relationships: A middle school casestudy.</i> Columbus, OH: National Middle School Association.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-6\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Marzano, R. (1992). <i>A different kind of classroom: Teaching with dimensions of learning.</i> Alexandria, VA: Association for Supervision and Curriculum Development.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-7\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-7\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Zahorik, J.A., &amp; Dichanz, H. (1994). \"Teaching for understanding in German schools\", <i>Educational Leadership</i>, 5(5), 75-77.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Atlantic-8\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Atlantic_8-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Atlantic_8-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Atlantic_8-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Atlantic_8-3\"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Oppenheimer, Todd (1999). \"Schooling the imagination\". <i>The Atlantic Monthly</i>. <b>284</b> (3): 71\u201383. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Serial_Number\" title=\"International Standard Serial Number\">ISSN</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.worldcat.org/issn/0160-6514\">0160-6514</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Atlantic+Monthly&amp;rft.atitle=Schooling+the+imagination&amp;rft.volume=284&amp;rft.issue=3&amp;rft.pages=71-83&amp;rft.date=1999&amp;rft.issn=0160-6514&amp;rft.aulast=Oppenheimer&amp;rft.aufirst=Todd&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ALoop+%28education%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<